Most likely, from the moment that one of the values is not convertible to a Java Enum constant name, JAXB generates fallback names like VALUE_1, VALUE_2, etc.

This is the case when the values are numbers, like &quot;1.2&quot;, 1.3&quot;, etc.

In your example the enumeration starts with value &quot; &quot;, no match for a Java constant name.

In those cases you will need to tell JAXB which Java Enum Constant name you want, for **every** enumeration value in that particular XSD enumeration restriction.

Like we did for the MODS 3.6 xsd:

``` xml
&lt;xs:element name=&quot;mods&quot; type=&quot;modsDefinition&quot;/&gt;
&lt;!--  --&gt;
&lt;xs:complexType name=&quot;modsDefinition&quot;&gt;
	&lt;xs:group ref=&quot;modsGroup&quot; maxOccurs=&quot;unbounded&quot;/&gt;
	&lt;xs:attribute name=&quot;ID&quot; type=&quot;xs:ID&quot;/&gt;
	&lt;xs:attribute name=&quot;version&quot;&gt;
		&lt;xs:simpleType&gt;
			&lt;xs:restriction base=&quot;xs:string&quot;&gt;
				&lt;xs:enumeration value=&quot;3.6&quot;/&gt;
				&lt;xs:enumeration value=&quot;3.5&quot;/&gt;
				&lt;xs:enumeration value=&quot;3.4&quot;/&gt;
				&lt;xs:enumeration value=&quot;3.3&quot;/&gt;
